default&#xa0;defaultResponse to select questionsdefault&#xa0;defaultQ1. defaultHow robust are the conclusions in the AR5 Physical defaultScience Basis report? Have the IPCC adequately addresses criticisms of previous reports? How much scope is there to question the report’s conclusions?default&#xa0;default1. 
defaultWe note that, 
defaultat the time of the Select Committee’s inquiry, the IPCC has only published a version of
default working group I’s contribution to the Fifth Assessment Report that has not been fully copy edited. Although the main findings of the report are unlikely to be different in the final version of the report, which is due for publication in January 2014, ther
defaulte may be some 
defaultsmall but significant changes to the text, for instance with respect to carbon emissions budgets.
default&#xa0;
default2. Working group I’s contribution to the Fifth Assessment Report
default is the most comprehens
defaultive 
defaultreview
default of the 
defaultevidence for the 
defaultphysical 
defaultscience basi
defaults of climate change that has ever been written. It has been prepared 
defaultby 259 scientific experts from 
defaultuniversities and research institutes in 39 countries, who have
default reviewed all of the available 
defaultevidence and research, including thousands of scientific papers
default. More tha
defaultn 9000 individual 
defaultscientific pape
defaultrs are cited within the report. 
defaultIt is also one of the most rigorously reviewed scientific docume
defaultnts in history, with more than 
default50,000 comments made during a review process for earlier dr
defaultafts that was made open to 
defaultall 
defaultexperts around the world.
default 
defaultThe report has been written for the 195 member governments of the IPCC, and represents the most authoritative assessment of the state of knowledge about
default the physical science basis of 
defaultclimate change. It should also inform decis
defaultion-making at
default local, regional, national and 
defaultinternational level.
default&#xa0;
default3. While working group I’s contribution to the IPCC Fifth Assessment Report shows increases in knowledge and understanding about the physical science basis for climate change since the publi
defaultcation in 2007 of the Fourth Assessment Report, the fundamental conclusions are the same: the Earth is 
defaultwarming primarily due to human activities, and there is a high likelihood of a rise in global average 
defaultsurface 
defaulttemperature of much more than 2˚C, and othe
defaultr very significant changes in the global climate, by the end of this century if annual emissions of greenhouse gases are not sharply reduced.
default&#xa0;
default4. The contribution of working group I of the Fifth Assessment Report is the most authoritative report on the 
defaultphysical science basis of climate change that has ever been published. However, in some minor respects, it is already out of date by virtue of the fact that no papers that were accepted after 15 March 2013 for publication have been considered. This is part
defaulticularly important, for instance, in relation to the so-called recent slowdown in the rise of global average surface temperature.
default&#xa0;
default5
default. It should also be noted that the contribution of working group I to previous IPCC assessment reports may have under-estimated the pace at which climate change is occurring. Brysse 
defaultet al.
default (2012) concluded 
defaultthat 
default“
defaultat least some of the key attributes of globa
defaultl warming from increased atmospheric greenhouse gases have been under-predicted, particularly in IPCC assessments of the physical science, by Working Group I”
default.
default&#xa0;
default6. It is a matter of some concern that the contribution of working group I to the Fifth Assessm
defaultent Report intentionally omitted any explicit consideration of the overall consequences of a rise in global average surface temperature of more than 2˚C, which all governments have agreed s
defaulthould be avoided. This omission
default is perhaps the biggest shortcoming 
defaultof working group I’s contribution to the IPCC Fifth Assessment Report.
default&#xa0;
default7. 
defaultFollowing the discovery in 2010 of a small but significant mistake in the contribution of working group II to the Fourth Assessment Report, the IPCC invited the InterAcademy Council
default (IAC) to review its processes and procedures The report of the IAC’s review, published in 2010, did not make any specific criticisms of the contribution of working group I, but made a number of recommendations for improving the preparation of assessment r
defaulteports. Many of these recommendations were implemented during the compilation of working group I’s contribution to the Fifth Assessment Report.
default&#xa0;
default8
default. T
defaulthe IPCC sought to allow any interested individuals or organisations to participate in the review of early d
defaultrafts of working group I’s contribution, including a number of so-called climate change ‘sceptics’
default. 
defaultOne of these ‘sceptics’, 
defaultAlex Rawls, 
defaultpublished a draft of working group I’s contribution, in clear breach of the agreem
defaultent undertaken by all reviewers, and 
defaultattempted to misrepresent its contents (see Ward, 2012). The other contributions to the Fifth Assessment Report have also suffered similar breaches in what appears to be a concerted effort by climate change ‘sceptics’ to subvert and undermine the IPCC proc
defaultess.
default&#xa0;
default9. 
defaultThere was also a co-ordinated effort by the Global Warming Policy Foundation and its supporters to mislead the public and policy-makers through inaccurate articles 
defaultcriticising
default the contribution of working group I after the Summary for Policymakers 
defaultwas published on 27 September. Some of the most blatant efforts are described in Ward (2013a). We note that possibly the most egregious article was produced by Rt Hon Peter Lilley MP, who is a member of the Select Committee and Vice-Chairman of Tethys Petr
defaultoleum, for ‘City A.M.’ (Ward 2013b). Mr Lilley not only misrepresented the content of the Summary for Policymakers, but also provided a false portrayal of the IPCC and its processes.
default&#xa0;defaultQ2. To what extent does AR5 reflect the range of views among climate defaultscientists?default&#xa0;default10
default. There is a clear scientific consensus that the Earth is warming due to human activities, such as burning fossil fuels and deforestation. There are four main ways in which this consensus manifests itself
default (Ward &amp; Hicks, 2013)
default.
default First, t
defaulthe 259
default authors of 
defaultthe contribution of
default 
defaultIPCC 
defaultworking group I 
defaultto the Fifth Assessment Report 
defaulthave assessed all of the available research and 
default 
defaultevidence and concluded that it is 95 per cent probable that most of the war
defaultming since 1950 is 
defaultdue to human activities.
default Seco
defaultnd, a
defaultnalyses of peer-reviewed journal papers (e.g. Oreskes, 2004; Powell, 2012; Cook et al., 2013)
default 
defaultshow that less than 1 per cent disagree that human activities are th
defaulte major contributor to climate 
defaultchange.
default Third, s
defaulturveys (e.g. Doran &amp; Zimmerman, 2009) show
default that more than 97 per cent of climate researchers who are publishing scientific papers agree that human activity is a sig
defaultnificant contributor to rising 
defaultglobal average temperature.
default Fourth, a
defaultll of the world’s major scientific organisations, including nation
defaultal academies of science such as the Royal Society, agree that human activities are the major contributor to recent climate change.
