default&#xa0;defaultQ6. Has AR5 sufficiently explained the reasons behind the widely reported hiatus in the global surface temperature record?default&#xa0;default1
default4
default. 
defaultThere has been a 
defaultcampaign by clim
defaultate change ‘sceptics’ to mislead the public, journalists and policy-makers about the significance of the 
defaultlower
default rate of increase in global average surface temperature since 1998 compared with the long-term warming rate since 19
default51
default. IPCC working group I was f
defaultorced to respond to this campaign by addressing the issue explicitly in its contribution to the Fifth Assessment Report.
default It attributed
default the 
defaultlower
default rate of warming 
defaultsince 1998 
defaultmainly 
defaultto
default the impact of 
defaultshort-term natural factors that mask the warming effec
defaultt of greenhouse gases, such as 
defaultan increase in the amount of heat absorbed by the deeper oce
defaultans compared with the surface, 
defaultan increase in the amount of volcanic particles in the a
defaulttmosphere which block out some 
defaultsunlight and cause cooling, and a cyclical redu
defaultction in the amount of radiation from the sun
default.
default&#xa0;
default15
default. The contribution of working group I only considered research papers that were accepted before 15 March 2013 for publication. Since that date, new papers have been published which have added to the knowledge and understanding of the apparent lower rate of
default warming since 1998. For instance, a paper by Cowtan and Way, published in November 2013, concluded that the 
defaultMet Office’s 
defaultHadCRUT4 record of global average surface temperature has significantly underestimated the rate of warming since 1997.
default&#xa0;
default16
default. It is impo
defaultrtant to consider the lower rate of warming since 1998 within the context of the longer record of global average temperature. T
defaulthere are many other such tempora
defaultry periods of higher and lower 
defaultrates of warming, and even of cooling, within the temperature re
defaultco
defaultrd. For instance, the linear 
defaulttrend in average annual temperature for the 43-year pe
defaultriod between 1970 and 2012, as 
defaultrecorded in the Met Office’s HadCRUT4 dataset, is +0.165°C per
default decade, but there are shorter 
default15-year periods of lower warming rates, such as 0
default.098°C per
default decade between 1979 and 1993, 
defaultand 0.044°C per decade between 1998 and 2012 
default(Ward and Hicks, 2013).
