defaultQ7. Do the AR5 defaultPhysical Science Basis report’s conclusions strengthen or weaken the economic case for action to prevent dangerous climate change?default&#xa0;default17
default. 
defaultWorking group I’s contribution to the Fifth Assessment Report does not offer an assessment of the economic impacts of cl
defaultimate change, which will be considered in the contribution of working group II, due for publication in 2014.
default However, working group I does indicate both that both atmospheric concentrations of carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases, and some of the phys
defaultical impacts of climate change, such as the reduction in the area of Arctic sea ice, have increased since the publication of the IPCC Fourth Assessment Report in 2007.
default&#xa0;
default18
default. Stern (2013) warns that many analyses significantly under-estimate the potential ec
defaultonomic 
defaultconsequences
default of unmanaged climate change because of their reliance on the outputs of models, inclu
defaultding those assessed in working group I’s contribution to the Fifth Assessment Report, which omit some of the largest risks. Stern (2013) states: “
defaultScien
defaulttists describe the scale of the risks from unmanage
defaultd climate change as potentially 
defaultimmense. However, the scientific models, because they
default omit key factors that are hard 
defaultto capture precisely, appear to substantially underesti
defaultmate these risks. Many economic 
defaultmodels add further gross underassessment of risk bec
defaultause the assumptions built into 
defaultthe economic 
defaultmodelling
default on growth, damages and risks, 
defaultcome close to assuming directly 
defaultthat the impacts and costs will be modest and close 
defaultto excluding the possibility of 
defaultcat
defaultastrophic outcomes. A new generation of models is
default needed in all three of climate 
defaultscience, impact and economics with a still stronger 
defaultfocus on lives and livelihoods, 
defaultincluding the risks of large-scale migration and conflicts.
default”
